The '''1941 Atlantic hurricane season''' was the period during 1941 in which tropical cyclones formed in the [[Atlantic hurricane|Atlantic Basin]]. It was a relatively inactive [[Atlantic hurricane season|hurricane season]], with only six known storms. It officially began on June 16, 1941 and lasted until November 1, 1941.<ref>{{cite news|author=|title= Don't Get Alarmed But Hurricane Season Is Now Officially 'Open'|date=June 16, 1941|publisher=''Port Arthur News''|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://www.thehurricanearchive.com/Viewer.aspx?img=30939126_clean&firstvisit=true&src=search&currentResult=0&currentPage=0}}</ref> These dates delimit the period of each year when most [[tropical cyclone]]s tend to form in the [[Atlantic basin]]. Of the six cyclones, four attained hurricane status, and two became major hurricanes. The season had an abnormally late start; the first system formed on September 11, nearly two months after the official beginning date. The season was also short-lived, as all six storms developed in rapid succession. On September 23, three hurricanes existed simultaneously in the Atlantic basin.

In total, the season resulted in about 63 fatalities and over $10 million in damages.<ref name="MWR"/> The first and last storms of the season were largely insignificant, although the second, fourth, and fifth storms had considerable effects. One hurricane struck [[Texas]] and [[Louisiana]] in late September, disrupting the [[Louisiana Maneuvers]]. Among the most significant storms to impact the [[United States]] was [[1941 Florida hurricane|Hurricane Five]], which made landfall in [[Florida]] at Category 3 intensity, inflicting widespread damage. Another major storm<U+2014>Hurricane Four<U+2014>traversed the Caribbean, leaving 47 men dead at sea.
