==Storms==
===Tropical Storm One===
{{Infobox Hurricane Small
|Basin=Atl
|Image=Tropical storm September 12, 1941 weather map.jpg
|Alt=Weather map depicting a storm in the Gulf of Mexico, south of Louisiana
|Track=1941 Atlantic tropical storm 1 track.png
|Track alt=A Gulf of Mexico storm track starts about halfway between the Florida panhandle and Yucatan, heads west and a bit north, and makes landfall near the Texas<U+2013>Louisiana border.
|Formed=September 11
|Dissipated=September 16
|1-min winds=40
|Pressure=1003
}}
The first storm of the 1941 season formed on September 11 in the northern [[Gulf of Mexico]]. This was an abnormally late start to an Atlantic hurricane season: only on two other occasions between 1887 and 1941 had no storms developed prior to September 11.<ref name="MWR"/> The storm moved slowly in a generally westward direction for the next few days, peaking as a moderate tropical storm with winds of 45&nbsp;mph (75&nbsp;km/h). It made landfall along the northern [[Texas]] coast between [[Galveston, Texas|Galveston]] and [[Port Arthur, Texas|Port Arthur]] where it caused only minor damage.<ref name="MWR"/> Near 0000 UTC on September 16, the storm deteriorated into a depression, and dissipated a few hours later.<ref name="hurdat"/>
{{clear}}

===Hurricane Two===
{{main|1941 Texas hurricane}}
{{Infobox Hurricane Small
|Basin=Atl
|Image=Hurricane September 24, 1941 weather map.jpg
|Alt=Weather map depicting a storm moving inland over Texas
|Track=1941 Atlantic hurricane 2 track.png
|Track alt=A Gulf of Mexico storm track starts about halfway west of the the Florida panhandle, heads west, completes a clockwise loop, and heads northeast towards Texas.
|Formed=September 16
|Dissipated=September 24
|1-min winds=80
|Pressure=971
}}
Tropical Storm Two formed off the western coast of [[Florida]] on September 16 and began moving west-southwest.<ref name="hurdat"/> Operationally, the cyclone was first observed on September 18, to the south of [[Louisiana]]. After intensifying to a Category 1 hurricane, the storm began drifting southward towards the [[Yucatan Peninsula]], ultimately executing a clockwise loop. By September 21 it had turned northward before assuming a more northwestward course. It moved across the western Gulf of Mexico and went ashore in [[Texas]] on September 23. It curved towards the northeast, passing just east of [[Houston, Texas|Houston]], and accelerated as it continued to move inland. The cyclone transitioned into an [[extratropical storm]] on September 24, and was last recorded in southern [[Quebec]].<ref name="MWR"/>

Warnings and advisories declared in response to the storm were widely distributed, and approximately 25,000 people in the area evacuated their homes.<ref name="MWR"/> Officials completed various precautionary measures.<ref>{{cite news|author=|title=Hurricane Poised to Hit Texas|date=September 23, 1941|publisher=''The Evening Independent''|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=a6kLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KVUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6415,5231439}}</ref> Wind gusts along the coast reached up to {{convert|100|mph|km/h|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Houston, Tex., Feels Lash of Coastal Storm|date=September 24, 1941|publisher=''The Chicago Daily Tribune''|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/467687442.html?dids=467687442:467687442&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic}}</ref> and high [[storm tides]] were recorded.<ref name="MWR"/> The hurricane inflicted severe damage; destruction to property was worth an estimated $2 million, with an additional $5 million in damage to crops, notably rice and cotton. Overall, the cyclone killed four people.<ref name="MWR"/> The hurricane affected the southern Louisiana region one week before the [[Louisiana Maneuvers]], a prelude to [[World War II]]. Heavy rainfall triggered flooding and swelled rivers, and army vehicles became stuck in the mud as a result.<ref>{{cite web|author=Velmer Lenora Smith|title=World War II&nbsp;<U+2014> Louisiana Maneuvers|date=|publisher=Beauregard Parish Library|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://www.beau.org/~velmer/local/ww2.html}}</ref> The inclement weather forced hundreds of military aircraft to move inland for shelter.<ref name="headed">{{cite news|author=|title=Gulf Storm Is Headed For Texas|date=September 22, 1941|work=The Evening Independent|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aqkLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KVUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3460,5129833}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Hurricane Three===
{{Infobox Hurricane Small
|Basin=Atl
|Image=Hurricane September 22, 1941 weather map.jpg
|Alt=Weather map depicting a storm off the southeast coast of the United States
|Track=1941 Atlantic hurricane 3 track.png
|Track alt=A storm track starts east of the Florida panhandle and moves eastward; after turning towards the north, the track terminates near Nova Scotia.
|Formed=September 18
|Dissipated=September 25
|1-min winds=70
|Pressure=995
}}
Early on September 18, squally weather was reported throughout the Atlantic coast of Florida, with indications that a circulation center was present {{convert|150|mi|km|abbr=on}} offshore.<ref name="MWR"/> It is estimated that a tropical storm had formed at around this time.<ref name="hurdat"/> The cyclone began to intensity as it briefly moved northeastward, before abruptly executing an eastward turn. It attained Category 1 hurricane status on September 19, and completed a clockwise loop the next day. It then tracked northwestward toward [[North Carolina]], but began to recurve away from land late on October 22. It weakened into a tropical storm shortly afterward. The system dissipated on September 25 to the south of [[Nova Scotia]]. The storm had little or no effect on land, but caused significant delays for North Atlantic shipping. One vessel en route from [[Cura<U+00E7>ao]] to [[New York]] encountered the storm on two separate occasions, recording Force 8 winds on the [[Beaufort scale]] both times.<ref name="MWR"/>

{{clear}}

===Hurricane Four===
{{Infobox Hurricane Small
|Basin=Atl
|Image=1941 Central American hurricane track.png
|Alt=A map depicting the track of a storm that traverses the Caribbean Sea from east-west and strikes Central America.
|Formed=September 23
|Dissipated=September 30
|1-min winds=105
|Prepressure=<U+2264>
|Pressure=993
}}
On September 23, a minor area of disturbed weather was observed about {{convert|75|mi|km|abbr=on}} to the northwest of [[Barbados]].<ref name="MWR"/> It is estimated that it developed into a tropical storm shortly thereafter.<ref name="hurdat"/> Tracking westward, it passed just south of [[St. Lucia]] and emerged into the [[Caribbean Sea]]. By September 25, the storm had reached hurricane strength.<ref name="MWR"/> Still intensifying, the storm continued generally westward and reached its peak at Category 3 on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]].<ref name="hurdat"/> By September 27, the hurricane was situated near [[Cape Gracias a Dios]], [[Honduras]], and accelerated as it moved across the northernmost stretch of the country. After briefly entering the [[Gulf of Honduras]], it moved ashore again in the country, about {{convert|70|mi|km|abbr=on}} south of [[Belize]]. Gradually weakening, the storm continued inland and weakened to a tropical storm by September 29. The storm emerged over the [[Bay of Campeche]] as a tropical depression and made a final landfall on [[Veracruz]].<ref name="MWR"/>

Approximately 47 lives were lost at sea due to the hurricane. The ''SS Ethel Sakel'' displayed a "sinking" message on September 25, about {{convert|125|mi|km|abbr=on}} north of [[Aruba]]; she later went down with 20 of her 33 crew members. Two other ships sent out distress signals, one of which capsized, all hands lost. Damage on land was also extensive, and three people drowned at Cape Gracias, which was largely destroyed by the storm. Coastal flooding in the town was severe.<ref name="MWR"/> In Belize, forests sustained major damage. For example, in the Melinda region, high winds brought down about about 10% of the large pines.<ref name="tree in Belize">{{cite report|author=Jon Friesner|title=Hurricanes in Belize|date=April 1993|publisher=Belize Forest Department|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://biological-diversity.info/Downloads/huricanesinbelize.pdf}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Hurricane Five===
{{main|1941 Florida hurricane}}
{{Infobox Hurricane Small
|Basin=Atl
|Image=1941 Florida hurricane Daily Weather Map.jpg
|Alt=Weather map depicting a storm approaching southeast Florida
|Track=1941 Atlantic hurricane 5 track.png
|Track alt=The path of a storm that begins well to the east of the Florida peninsula, and after moving westward and striking Florida, it curves northeast and re-enters the Atlantic Ocean. 
|Formed=October 3
|Dissipated=October 13
|1-min winds=105
|Pressure=<U+2264>964
}}
Tropical Storm Five was first observed to the north of the [[Virgin Islands]] on October&nbsp;3. The storm tracked generally westward through The Bahamas, reaching peak winds of {{convert|120|mph|km/h}}, which corresponds to a Category&nbsp;3 hurricane on the modern-day Saffir<U+2013>Simpson Hurricane Scale. After moving across southern Florida the hurricane emerged into the [[Gulf of Mexico]] and made another [[landfall (meteorology)|landfall]] along the [[Florida Panhandle]]. Turning toward the north and northeast, it crossed [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and [[South Carolina]], and entered the [[Atlantic Ocean]] on October 8. The storm fully dissipated several days later.<ref name="MWR"/>

Preparations for the storm were extensive; residents boarded up homes and businesses, while evacuations were recommended in some coastal areas.<ref>{{cite book|author=Barnes, Jay|title=Florida's Hurricane History|year=2007|publisher=Chapel Hill Press|isbn=0807830682|page=162}}</ref> In the Bahamas, where winds reached {{convert|104|mph|km/h}}, the storm killed three people. The city of [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]] was struck particularly hard. In Florida, damage was relatively severe, and included the deaths of several people. High winds brought down trees and powerlines, though the storm was characterized by highly unusual rainfall patterns. Storm surge in the [[Everglades]] region flooded local streets. As the storm progressed northward, the city of [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]] suffered widespread power outages and damage to numerous vehicles. Throughout the state, the hurricane inflicted $675,000 (1941&nbsp;USD) in damages. The cyclone later killed one person in Georgia.<ref name="rain">{{cite thesis|degree=Sc.D|author=Edward Morgan Brooks|title=An Unusual Rainfall Distribution in a Hurricane|year=1945|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://dspace.mit.edu/bitstream/handle/1721.1/13079/26336365.pdf?sequence=1|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name="MWR"/>
{{clear}}

===Tropical Storm Six===
{{Infobox Hurricane Small
|Basin=Atl
|Image=Tropical storm October 21, 1941 weather map.jpg
|Alt=Weather map depicting a storm approaching Florida from the west
|Track=1941 Atlantic tropical storm 6 track.png
|Track alt=Map of Florida depicting the track of a tropical storm, which starts north of Hispaniola, heads westward, and moves ashore in the United States.
|Formed=October 15
|Dissipated=October 22
|1-min winds=45
|Pressure=1002
}}
A tropical storm formed on October 15, and passed through the southern [[Bahamas]]. It crossed the [[Florida Straits]], and reached its peak intensity with winds of 50 mph (85 km/h) on October 20, after entering the eastern Gulf of Mexico and turning towards the north.<ref name="hurdat">{{cite web|author=Atlantic hurricane research division|year=2009|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/tracks1851to2008_atl_reanal.txt|title=Atlantic hurricane database (HURDAT) "best track" (1851<U+2013>2008)|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administrations|accessdate=November 6, 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5gWnyE3WS|archivedate=2009-05-04|deadurl=no}}</ref> It curved northeastward and made landfall at [[Cedar Key, Florida]].<ref name="MWR">{{cite web|author=Howard C. Sumner|title=North Atlantic Tropical Disturbances of 1941|publisher=Weather Bureau|year=1942|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/general/lib/lib1/nhclib/mwreviews/1941.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> After pushing inland, the storm stalled and weakened to a tropical depression on October 21 before dissipating fully the next day.<ref name="hurdat"/>

The storm's slow forward motion over the state of Florida led to heavy widespread precipitation, locally amounting to {{convert|10|to|15|in|mm|abbr=on}}. Gale-force winds were also reported. Some flood damage occurred throughout the affected locations.<ref name="MWR"/> An infant was killed following the destruction of a house, possibly related to a [[tornado]] spawned by the tropical storm; the baby's parents also sustained injuries.<ref>{{cite web|author=|title=Baby Perishes in Florida Storm|date=October 21, 1941|publisher=''The New York Times''|accessdate=November 6, 2009|url=http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20D14FF3F5E1A7A93C3AB178BD95F458485F9}}</ref>
{{clear}}

